On Wed, Feb 14, 2024 at 1:45 PM Joe Schaefer <joe@sunstarsys.com> wrote:
>
> Assuming Google hasn't found any more fuzzing vulnerabilities with apreq, we should call the subproject done after releasing it, rolling any new efforts into httpd's internal copy of the codebase for the next major release of httpd.
>
> Sound like a plan?  I can get the ball rolling on the RM process assuming I still have working login (or can reacquire it via pw reset.

I think another apreq release makes sense.

But from the few relevant threads over the years (many on private
lists), there seems to be little maintainer support for apreq much
less apreq embedded in httpd. If there ever were a release branched
from trunk, I don't think it's likely the embedded apreq would
survive.  I think it's a big consideration for what's done with the
standalone tree.
